  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="ITA69">
<l>kōvāki mānilaṅ kāttunaṅ kaṇmukappē</l>
<l>māvēkic celkiṉṟa maṉṉavarum – pūmēvuñ</l>
<l>ceṅkamala nāpiyāṉ cēvaṭikkē yēḻpiṟappun</l>
<l>taṇkamala mēyntār tamar</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Even as kings, who, having become kings [and] protecting the vast land,</l>
<l>move<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here we see one of the two proper present tense forms that are found in the early Antāti-s, this one a peyareccam, while in Pū. 87.1 there is a 1st person singluar, aṟikiṉṟēṉ.</note> on horse back in front of our eyes, his people</l>
<l>through all seven births cover with cool lotuses only the red feet</l>
<l>of him in whose navel dwells a red lotus flower.<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here Tārkkatīrttar Rāmānujācāryar suggest to change back the word order that had been altered for the sake of etukai to cem kamalam pū mēvum.</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
